Make the four external video controls null-safe, exactly mirroring the sibling resetViewVideosTimer() at :91-95 which already guards mCurrentView. Change the one-line overrides to:
  void startViewVideos() override { if (mCurrentView != nullptr) mCurrentView->startViewVideos(); }
  void stopViewVideos() override { if (mCurrentView != nullptr) mCurrentView->stopViewVideos(); }
  void pauseViewVideos() override { if (mCurrentView != nullptr) mCurrentView->pauseViewVideos(); }
  void muteViewVideos() override { if (mCurrentView != nullptr) mCurrentView->muteViewVideos(); }
This fixes BOTH W7.0 and W6.0 (identical call sites: main.cpp:557 startViewVideos / :561 pauseViewVideos reached on a gamescope focus transition while the no-games dialog is up and mCurrentView is still null). Do the guard in ViewController.h (not in main.cpp) so every external caller is protected, matching the file's own convention.

Replace the raw `SwitchComponent* sc {switchComp.get()}` capture (line 181) used inside the ASYNC RESPONSE lambda with a std::weak_ptr, mirroring GuiMadPageBackends.cpp:506-540. Concretely:
  (a) After `auto switchComp = std::make_shared<SwitchComponent>();` add: `std::weak_ptr<SwitchComponent> weakSc {switchComp};`
  (b) Keep the SYNCHRONOUS read in the setCallback body (`const bool on {sc->getState()}` at :183) using the raw `sc` — that fires from the live component's own input() so it cannot dangle (same justification as the existing comment at :177-180). Actually simplest: also lock weakSc there for uniformity, but it is not required.
  (c) In the RESPONSE callback (the `[this, name, on, sc](bool ok, ...)` lambda at :193), capture weakSc instead of sc and guard every deref:
        [this, name, on, weakSc](bool ok, const rapidjson::Value& payload) {
            auto sc = weakSc.lock();
            if (!ok) {
                if (sc) sc->setState(!on);
                footer()->flash(...); return;
            }
            applyConfig(MadJson::getMember(payload, "splash"));
            if (sc) sc->setState(mPool.count(name) > 0);
            footer()->flash(...);
        }
Note: applyConfig() must still run even if sc is gone (it updates mPool used by the caption), so do NOT early-return on !sc before applyConfig in the ok branch — only guard the setState() calls. This matches the Backends rollback pattern (`if (auto chipRow = weakChips.lock()) chipRow->setChipState(...)`).

Stop asserting setBlockInput every frame; only drive it on the focus TRANSITION, alongside the existing pause/resume video logic. Currently :549 does an UNCONDITIONAL `window->setBlockInput(!esHasFocus);` every loop iteration, which clobbers ViewController's intentional input-blocks (launch animation via triggerGameLaunch() ViewController.h:101, rescan, return-from-game swallow). Fix: delete the per-frame write at :549 and fold the block into the transition branch at :555-563 so it only fires when esHasFocus changes:
    static bool sHadFocus {true};
    if (esHasFocus != sHadFocus) {
        window->setBlockInput(!esHasFocus);
        if (esHasFocus) { ViewController::getInstance()->startViewVideos(); guideHeld = false; }
        else { ViewController::getInstance()->pauseViewVideos(); }
        sHadFocus = esHasFocus;
    }
Keep gamescopeFocus.init()/hasFocus() at the top (the esHasFocus value is still read every frame for the render-skip at :658). On focus LOSS we still block; on focus REGAIN we unblock once — and in between, ViewController's own setBlockInput(true)/(false) during launch/rescan is honored. (Initial state: the window starts unblocked and sHadFocus=true, matching today.)

Add a client-side safety reset so a missed input.lock 'locked:false' event can't wedge the panel forever. mInputLocked is set ONLY by the daemon's input.lock event (:148); if the daemon dies or drops the unlock, :411-412 swallows ALL input permanently. The capture modal is window-topmost while a capture is live, and GuiMadPanel::update() only runs when the PANEL is topmost (the comment at :458-459 states this). So: when update() runs (panel is topmost) AND no GuiMadCaptureModal is currently on the Window stack above us, there is no legitimate reason for the panel to be input-locked — clear it. Add near the top of update(), after poll():
    // Safety: the input lock is only valid while a capture/tester modal is live. If we are
    // being updated (panel is topmost) yet no capture modal is open, a 'locked:false' event
    // was missed (daemon died mid-capture) — release so input can't wedge forever.
    if (mInputLocked && !captureModalActive())
        mInputLocked = false;
Implement captureModalActive() by tracking the modal: GuiMadPanel already pushes GuiMadCaptureModal (it owns the push site). Simplest reliable signal: set a member `mCaptureModalOpen=true` when the panel pushes the modal and clear it in the modal's close path / when the panel next regains topmost. If a bool is awkward, an alternative is to check the existing onBackendReady() reset (:163) already covers the daemon-RESTART case — so W1.0's residual gap is only the 'daemon died but not yet restarted, modal already popped' window. Given mInputLockAllowNav exists, scope the reset to also clear mInputLockAllowNav. Keep it conservative: only clear when we are CERTAIN no modal is up.

Guard the rapidjson GetString() on the Wii accessory 'allowed' array, mirroring every other array loop in this codebase (e.g. the images loop in GuiMadPageSplash.cpp:60-63 checks IsString() first). Change:
    for (rapidjson::SizeType i {0}; i < allowedArr.Size(); ++i)
        extAllowed.emplace_back(allowedArr[i].GetString());
to:
    for (rapidjson::SizeType i {0}; i < allowedArr.Size(); ++i) {
        if (allowedArr[i].IsString())
            extAllowed.emplace_back(allowedArr[i].GetString());
    }
rapidjson's GetString() asserts (or returns garbage in release with assertions off) if the element is not a string; a malformed daemon payload would otherwise crash/UB here.

Guard against inverted bounds before std::clamp (std::clamp is UB if hi < lo). After computing lo/hi/step, add a swap:
    float lo {static_cast<float>(numberAt(setting, "min", 0.0))};
    float hi {static_cast<float>(numberAt(setting, "max", isFloat ? 2.5 : 9.0))};
    if (hi < lo) std::swap(lo, hi);
    const float step {...};
    const float cur {std::clamp(static_cast<float>(numberAt(setting, "value", lo)), lo, hi)};
(Drop the `const` on lo/hi or compute the swap before binding to const — easiest is to make lo/hi non-const as shown.) <algorithm> is already included for std::clamp; <utility> for std::swap is transitively available but add `#include <utility>` if the build complains. This also protects the downstream MadStepper which is constructed with (lo, hi) and whose setValue()/adjust() also assume mMin<=mMax.

Clamp mStep to a tiny positive floor in the constructor so adjust()'s `(mMax - mMin) / mStep` at :90 can't divide by zero. Change the member init at :33 from `, mStep {step}` to:
    , mStep {std::max(step, 1e-6f)}
Requires <algorithm> for std::max — already included at :13 (<cmath>) plus this file uses glm::clamp; add `#include <algorithm>` if not already present (it is needed for std::max). A mStep of 0 would today yield a division by zero in maxSteps/stepIndex (inf/NaN -> garbage clamp).

std::stoi at :425 still throws std::out_of_range for an all-digit string larger than INT_MAX, defeating the :419-424 non-digit guard's stated goal ('must not throw on the updater thread'). Replace the parse with a range-safe one. Simplest: keep the non-digit guard, then wrap the comparison:
    try {
        mNewVersion = (std::stoi(releaseType->releaseNum) > MAD_RELEASE_NUMBER);
    } catch (const std::exception& e) {
        LOG(LogWarning) << "ApplicationUpdater: release number \"" << releaseType->releaseNum
                        << "\" out of range — skipping";
        continue;
    }
Alternative (no exceptions): use std::strtol into a long and compare, treating overflow (errno==ERANGE) as 'skip'. Either is fine; the try/catch is the smallest diff. NOTE for completeness (CC.3): the Android branch at :409 has the same std::stoi(androidVersionCode) pattern — it is gated by !defined(__ANDROID__)/the #else so it does not compile in our Steam Deck build; leave it unless an Android build is ever targeted.

Install an XSetIOErrorHandler so a broken X connection to the gamescope server doesn't terminate ES-DE. Xlib's DEFAULT IO-error handler calls exit() when the connection drops (e.g. gamescope restarts) — and this code holds a long-lived Display* (mDisplay) polled every frame in hasFocus(). Add, in the anonymous namespace (near tryDisplay, inside the `#if defined(__linux__) && !defined(__ANDROID__)` block):
    int gamescopeIOErrorHandler(Display*) {
        // The gamescope X server went away. Returning here lets Xlib NOT exit();
        // we longjmp back so the caller can disable polling and fall back to 'focused'.
        std::longjmp(sXIOErrorJmp, 1);
    }
and a file-scope `std::jmp_buf sXIOErrorJmp;` plus `#include <csetjmp>`. Register it once in init() right after a Display is chosen (after :108 mDisplay=...):
    XSetIOErrorHandler(gamescopeIOErrorHandler);
Then guard the polling in hasFocus(): wrap the XGetWindowProperty round-trips with `if (setjmp(sXIOErrorJmp)) { mEnabled = false; mDisplay = nullptr; return true; }` at the top of the polling block (before the readCardinal calls at :146). On IO error: mark disabled, drop the dangling Display*, and fail toward 'focused' (input unblocked) — the same safe direction the code already uses for unreadable atoms (:148). IMPORTANT: an XIOErrorHandler must NOT return normally (Xlib will exit() if it does) — the longjmp is mandatory, which is why setjmp is used rather than a simple flag.

Add PR_SET_PDEATHSIG in the forked child so the wii-nav-bridge actually dies with ES-DE, making the existing comments at :88 ('PDEATHSIG would be its only lifeline') and :122 ('PDEATHSIG is the backup') TRUE. The header already advertises this (MadWiiBridge.h:11 'dies with ES-DE (stdin EOF + PR_SET_PDEATHSIG on the Python side)'). In the child branch right after fork (before the dup2 chain at :70, or at least before execlp at :80) add:
    prctl(PR_SET_PDEATHSIG, SIGTERM);
and add `#include <sys/prctl.h>` to the includes (the file already has csignal/fcntl/sys/wait/unistd). prctl is async-signal-safe and Linux-only, which is the sole target. This is a backstop to the primary EOF-on-stdin mechanism; both can coexist. Note the comment says 'PR_SET_PDEATHSIG on the Python side' — verify whether wii-nav-bridge.py ALSO sets it; if it does, this C++ add is belt-and-suspenders (harmless). If it does not, this is the real fix.

Cap the reader-thread line buffer so a daemon line with no newline can't grow unbounded. After `buffer.append(chunk, ...)` at :143, add a sanity cap on the un-newlined remainder. Simplest: after the inner newline-draining while-loop and the `buffer.erase(0, pos)` at :159, check:
    static constexpr size_t kMaxLineBytes {8 * 1024 * 1024};
    if (buffer.size() > kMaxLineBytes) {
        LOG(LogWarning) << "MadBackend: backend emitted a >8MB line with no newline — "
                           "treating the stream as corrupt and dropping the reader";
        break; // falls through to mDead=true; mReaderDone=true; like EOF
    }
Breaking out mirrors the EOF path (:162-163 set mDead/mReaderDone), so poll()'s death/restart handling kicks in cleanly. 8MB is generously above any legitimate NDJSON line (device lists, art payloads are KBs).

ASSESSMENT FIRST: This is LOW and somewhat speculative. writeLine() does a blocking write() to the daemon's stdin on the UI/render thread; if the daemon stops reading and the pipe fills (64KB default), the UI thread stalls. In practice the daemon drains continuously and requests are tiny NDJSON lines, so the pipe rarely fills. RECOMMENDED MINIMAL FIX: make the write non-blocking and treat EAGAIN as backend-died backpressure rather than a UI stall. In spawn(), after obtaining the write fd (mStdinFd = inPipe[1] at :119), set non-blocking: `fcntl(mStdinFd, F_SETFL, O_NONBLOCK);`. Then in writeLine() handle EAGAIN/EWOULDBLOCK in the `count == -1` path:
    if (count == -1 && (errno == EAGAIN || errno == EWOULDBLOCK)) {
        LOG(LogWarning) << "MadBackend: stdin pipe full — backend not draining, treating as dead";
        return false; // request() then sets mDead and completes EBACKEND_DIED
    }
(keep the existing EINTR retry at :423). The existing request() caller at :405-411 already converts a writeLine() false return into mDead + EBACKEND_DIED, so no new plumbing is needed. Do NOT spin-retry on EAGAIN (that would busy-wait the UI thread).

OPTIONAL hardening (INFO severity). Use RapidJSON's iterative (non-recursive) parser so a deeply-nested daemon line can't blow the stack. Change parseLine() at :27 from:
    doc.Parse(line.c_str(), line.length());
to:
    doc.Parse<rapidjson::kParseIterativeFlag>(line.c_str(), line.length());
rapidjson/document.h is already included (:12). kParseIterativeFlag bounds stack usage regardless of nesting depth; the trusted local daemon never sends deep nesting today, so this is purely defensive.

OPTIONAL defensive (INFO). Before reassigning mReaderThread, assert/ensure it is non-joinable, so a future code path that calls spawn() without a preceding shutdownChild()/join can't trip std::terminate (assigning to a joinable std::thread terminates). Today restart()->terminate()->shutdownChild() joins it (:479-486) before spawn(), so the invariant holds — this just makes it explicit. Add right before :125:
    if (mReaderThread.joinable()) {
        LOG(LogWarning) << "MadBackend: spawn() found a live reader thread — joining first";
        mReaderThread.join();
    }
(Only reached if mStdoutFd were still open; harmless otherwise.)

Add the degenerate-clip guard MadScrollView already has. MadTileGrid computes scale-aware dims at :213-214 then pushClipRect at :215-218 with NO check that the dims are >=1; pushClipRect treats a zero dimension as 'extend to screen edge', DISABLING clipping (tiles bleed outside a zero-height grid). Mirror MadScrollView.cpp:77-82: compute the int clipDim, then before pushClipRect add:
    const glm::ivec2 clipDim {static_cast<int>(std::round(dim.x)), static_cast<int>(std::round(dim.y))};
    if (clipDim.x < 1 || clipDim.y < 1)
        return;
and pass clipDim into pushClipRect instead of recomputing. (Restructure :215-218 to use clipDim.)

Guard the BASE policy parse the same way the LOCAL parse (lines 51-56) is already guarded. Replace lines 48-50 (`if POLICY_FILE.is_file(): with POLICY_FILE.open('rb') as f: base = tomllib.load(f)`) with a try/except: `if POLICY_FILE.is_file():
    try:
        with POLICY_FILE.open('rb') as f:
            base = tomllib.load(f)
    except (tomllib.TOMLDecodeError, OSError) as exc:
        print(f'controller-router: controller-policy.toml parse error ({exc}); routing disabled (RetroArch defaults).', file=sys.stderr)`. On failure `base` keeps its initialized `{"systems": {}}` value (line 47), so resolve_system returns None for every system and the launch proceeds un-routed (RetroArch defaults) instead of aborting. This makes the base file fail-soft, matching the existing comment intent at line 56 ('a broken local file must never break routing'). sys is already imported (line 16).

Same base-parse guard as 0.1/12.4 but on the MAD-panel surface (this is a DISTINCT file from routing.py — load_merged is what every MAD page calls). Replace lines 21-22 (`if POLICY.is_file(): base = tomllib.load(POLICY.open('rb'))`) with a try/except + context manager (also fixes the dormant file-handle leak noted in 1.3): `if POLICY.is_file():
    try:
        with POLICY.open('rb') as f:
            base = tomllib.load(f)
    except (tomllib.TOMLDecodeError, OSError):
        pass  # keep the safe default; a corrupt base must not brick the panel`. On failure `base` keeps its init value `{"systems": {}, "backends": {}}` (line 20). OPTIONAL ENHANCEMENT (only if cheap): have the caller / a wrapper emit a structured rpc event so the panel can surface 'controller-policy.toml has a syntax error' instead of silently empty pages — but the minimal correct fix is the try/except + safe default. Add `import tomllib` is already present (line 9).

quit() (1870-1875) calls only _gp_cleanup() + _cam_restore_driver() — it NEVER calls _cam_kill_ffmpeg() (so an orphaned ffmpeg keeps the V4L2 camera open, Sinden aim dead = 4.0) and never kills self._dp_proc (so an in-flight Daphne hypseus_capture SDL subprocess is orphaned = N0.1). The cleanest reuse-based fix: call the existing _clear() at the top of quit(), because _clear() (lines 1340-1389) ALREADY performs full deterministic page teardown — it kills _dp_proc (1350-1356), calls _cam_kill_ffmpeg() (1374-1375), _cam_restore_driver() (1376), _gp_cleanup() (1346), releases tester grabs, and cancels camera after-timers (1367-1373). Concretely, change quit() to: `def quit(self):
    _diag('MAD quit -> ES-DE')
    try: self._clear()
    except Exception: pass
    try: self._gp_cleanup()
    except Exception: pass
    self._cam_restore_driver()
    self.root.destroy()`. Keeping the explicit _gp_cleanup + _cam_restore_driver after _clear() is belt-and-suspenders (both are idempotent). _clear() is called on every page navigation so it is well-tested and safe; the module docstring (mad_gamepad_tester.py:11) even documents 'App._clear()/quit() calling self._gp_cleanup()'. ALTERNATIVE (more surgical if _clear() at quit-time is risky): in quit(), before _cam_restore_driver(), add `try: self._cam_kill_ffmpeg()
except Exception: pass` and `_p=getattr(self,'_dp_proc',None);
if _p is not None:
    try: _p.kill()
    except Exception: pass`. The _clear() reuse is preferred (covers tester grabs + after-timers too).

_cam_tick (2478-2488) guards only `if not self._cam_proc:` (truthiness of the retained Popen object) and never calls .poll(), so if ffmpeg dies on its own (camera busy/unplugged, driver still holding it) the page shows a frozen frame while still claiming 'live', and the dead child becomes a zombie until the user leaves the page. Fix: in _cam_tick, after `self._cam_after = None` and the existing `if not self._cam_proc: return`, detect death before re-arming. Insert: `if self._cam_proc.poll() is not None:
    self._cam_kill_ffmpeg()
    try:
        self._cam_lbl.config(image='', text='( camera busy / preview ended — press Preview to retry )')
    except Exception:
        pass
    try:
        self._cam_status.config(text='Preview ended (camera busy?). Press Preview to retry.')
    except Exception:
        pass
    self._cam_img = None
    return`. poll() also reaps the child (eliminating the zombie). _cam_kill_ffmpeg() (2398-2409) safely sets self._cam_proc=None. Place this BEFORE the PhotoImage load block (2482-2487) so a dead feed is caught immediately rather than retried forever.
